  "response": "Here are some highly recommended books for learning SQL:\n\nBeginner Level:\n1. \"SQL Queries for Mere Mortals\" by John L. Viescas\n- Great for absolute beginners\n- Simple, clear explanations\n- Practical examples\n\n2. \"Head First SQL\" by Lynn Beighley\n- Visual, engaging learning style\n- Easy to understand for newcomers\n- Covers fundamental concepts\n\nIntermediate Level:\n3. \"SQL Cookbook\" by Anthony Molinaro\n- Practical problem-solving approach\n- Advanced query techniques\n- Covers multiple database systems\n\n4. \"Learning SQL\" by Alan Beaulieu\n- Comprehensive overview\n- Hands-on exercises\n- Covers SQL standard techniques\n\nAdvanced Level:\n5. \"SQL Performance Tuning\" by Grant Fritchey\n- Focuses on query optimization\n- Advanced performance techniques\n- Practical database optimization strategies\n\n6. \"Designing Data-Intensive Applications\" by Martin Kleppmann\n- Deeper understanding of database systems\n- Covers broader database concepts\n- More theoretical but extremely insightful\n\nOnline Resources:\n- W3Schools SQL Tutorial\n- Mode Analytics SQL Tutorial\n- SQLZoo\n\nRecommended complementary practice platforms:\n- LeetCode\n- HackerRank\n- SQLPad",
